1. INTRODUCTION

Fractals are beautiful pictures. There exist many (and also some
good) programs to calculate these pictures in fancy colors on your
screen. But wouldn't it be nice to print these pictures in a high
resolution onto a piece of paper?

Exactly this is what PrintFractal does.

@EndNode

@Node "REQUIREMENTS" "PrintFractal.guide"
@Next "INSTALLATION"
@Prev "INTRODUCTION"
@Toc  "Main"

2. REQUIREMENTS

SOFTWARE

PrintFractal needs at least OS2.0 to run. With OS2.1 you can benefit
from localization features.

HARDWARE

PrintFractal should run on all Amigas.

Of course, you'll need a printer.

@EndNode

@Node "INSTALLATION"
@Prev "REQUIREMENTS"
@Next "PROGRAMSTART"
@Toc  "Main"

3. INSTALLATION

There's an installer script provided which does all the necessary work
for you. Simply click on the icon from Workbench and it will guide you
through the installation step by step.

@EndNode

@Node "PROGRAMSTART"
@Next "WORKBENCH USAGE"
@Prev "INSTALLATION"
@Toc  "Main"

4. Programstart

PrintFractal can be run either by Workbench or Shell.

     @{" Workbench usage       " Link "WORKBENCH USAGE"}
     @{" Shell usage           " Link "SHELL USAGE"}

@EndNode

@Node "WORKBENCH USAGE"
@Next "WORKBENCH USAGE (SCREENNAME)"
@Prev "PROGRAMSTART"
@Toc  "Main"

WORKBENCH USAGE

Run PrintFractal by clicking on its icon twice. The main window of
PrintFractal will now appear.

The program settings will be read from the tooltypes of the icon. You
should not change these tooltypes by hand but make your selections in
the main window of PrintFractal. Then use the menu Settings/Save
settings to make sure the settings will be the same at the next
program start.

Following tooltypes can`t be changed by using the program. You have to
edit them manually in the info window of your workbench. To do this,
select the icon of PrintFractal (click it once) and select the
workbench menu Icon/Info.

     @{" SCREENNAME            " Link "WORKBENCH USAGE (SCREENNAME)"}
     @{" FONTNAME              " Link "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTNAME)"}
     @{" FONTSIZE              " Link "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTSIZE)"}

@EndNode

@Node "WORKBENCH USAGE (SCREENNAME)"
@Next "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTNAME)"
@Prev "WORKBENCH USAGE"
@Toc  "Main"

WORKBENCH USAGE

SCREENNAME

If you want the main window to appear on a different public screen you
have to change the tooltype SCREENNAME.
Enter the name of the public screen as tooltype in the form
'SCREENNAME=<name>' (<name> is case sensitive).

If the selected public screen does not exist while you start
PrintFractal, the default public screen will be used.

@EndNode

@Node "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTNAME)"
@Next "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTSIZE)"
@Prev "WORKBENCH USAGE (SCREENNAME)"
@Toc  "Main"

WORKBENCH USAGE

FONTNAME

To select a differnt font use a tooltype 'FONTNAME=<name>.font'. Make
sure that your fontname ends with '.font'.

@EndNode

@Node "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTSIZE)"
@Next "SHELL USAGE"
@Prev "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTNAME)"
@Toc  "Main"

WORKBENCH USAGE

FONTSIZE

Select a different size of the font by using the tooltype 'FONTSIZE'.

@EndNode

@Node "SHELL USAGE"
@Next "SHELL USAGE (NAME)"
@Prev "WORKBENCH USAGE (FONTSIZE)"
@Toc  "Main"

To start PrintFractal from a shell, simply enter its name and press
return (the current directory has not to be the program directory; in
this case, of course, you have to add a complete path description).

At shell start PrintFractal accepts following options:

     @{" NAME                  " Link "SHELL USAGE (NAME)"}
     @{" SCREEN/K              " Link "SHELL USAGE (SCREEN)"}
     @{" NOGUI/S               " Link "SHELL USAGE (NOGUI)"}

@EndNode

@Node "SHELL USAGE (NAME)"
@Next "SHELL USAGE (SCREEN)"
@Prev "SHELL USAGE"
@Toc  "Main"

SHELL USAGE

NAME

With the option NAME you are able to name a parameter file which
PrintFractal will try to load at start.

The use of the keyword NAME is not necessary.

Examples:

PrintFractal NAME=Fractals/Julia_Fig8.pf
Programs:Print/PrintFractal Work:Print/Fractals/Mandebrot.pf

@EndNode

@Node "SHELL USAGE (SCREEN)"
@Next "SHELL USAGE (NOGUI)"
@Prev "SHELL USAGE (NAME)"
@Toc  "Main"

SHELL USAGE

SCREEN/K

The option SCREEN makes it possible to enter the name of a public
screen. PrintFractal will try to open its windows on this screen. If
this fails, PrintFractal will use the default public screen.

The use of the keyword SCREEN is necessary.

Example:

PrintFractal SCREEN=MeinBeispielBildschirm

@EndNode

@Node "SHELL USAGE (NOGUI)"
@Next "USAGE"
@Prev "SHELL USAGE (SCREEN)"
@Toc  "Main"

SHELL START

NOGUI/S

NOGUI acts as a switch. If you specify NOGUI, you force PrintFractal
not to open its main window. This is extremly useful if you want to
control PrintFractal by ARexx.

Attention: You cannot quit PrintFractal by using mouse or keyboard
with no main window open. The only way to quit will be to send the
command QUIT to the ARexx port of PrintFractal.

Example:

PrintFractal NOGUI

@EndNode

@Node "USAGE"
@Next "USAGE (FRACTAL SETTINGS)"
@Prev "PROGRAMSTART"
@Toc  "Main"

5. USAGE

The main window of PrintFractal consist of three sections.

  1. @{" Fractal settings      " Link "USAGE (FRACTAL SETTINGS)"}
  2. @{" Output settings       " Link "USAGE (OUTPUT SETTINGS)"}
  3. @{" Buttons               " Link "USAGE (BUTTONS)"}

Additionally there exists a menu from which you can make several
global settings.

  4. @{" Menu (Project)        " Link "MENU (PROJECT)"}
     @{" Menu (Buffer)         " Link "MENU (BUFFER)"}
     @{" Menu (Settings)       " Link "MENU (SETTINGS)"}

@EndNode

@Node "USAGE (FRACTAL SETTINGS)"
@Next "USAGE (OUTPUT SETTINGS)"
@Prev "USAGE"
@Toc  "Main"

FRACTAL SETTINGS

The following settings for the resulting fractal image can be made in
the upper part of the the main window.

TYPE

This button lets you choose between the two fractal types the program
is able to calculate.

LEFT, RIGHT, TOP, BOTTOM

Here you can enter the limits of the fractal image.


For each pixel of the image a mathematical process depending on the
following values will be calculated:

ITERATIONS

Here you can enter the maximum number of steps that will be calculated
for each pixel.

REAL, IMAG

These two values are the start values of the process. For mandelbrot
type of fractals they'll usually be 0.

LIMIT

Here you're able to enter the limit for the process. If the square of 
the distance of the current point in the process will be greater than
this value, the process is finished.

@EndNode

@Node "USAGE (OUTPUT SETTINGS)"
@Next "USAGE (BUTTONS)"
@Prev "USAGE (FRACTAL SETTINGS)"
@Toc  "Main"

OUTPUT SETTINGS

In the middle part of the main window you can make several settings
that will change the type and size of the resulting image.

MODE

Two differnt modes are available:

'mono': A pixel will be set if the process reaches the maximum depth.

'alternate': A pixel will be set if the number of steps to reach the
limit is odd.

BORDER

Here you can select the size of the border around the picture. If you
select 0, no border will be drawn.

WIDTH, HEIGHT

These two values select the size of the resulting image. Corresponding
to the button above these two fields the values are taken as
centimeter or inch.

@EndNode

@Node "USAGE (BUTTONS)"
@Next "MENU (PROJECT)"
@Prev "USAGE (OUTPUT SETTINGS)"
@Toc  "Main"

BUTTONS

In the bottom of the main window are three action buttons:

ABOUT

Shows some about information.

PRINT

Starts printing.

QUIT

Leaves the program.


In the upper part of the window is one additional button:

PREVIEW

Takes the current fractal settings and calculates a preview image.

@EndNode

@Node "MENU (PROJECT)"
@Next "MENU (BUFFER)"
@Prev "USAGE (BUTTONS)"
@Toc  "Main"

PROJECT MENU

LOAD ...

Load previously saved fractal and output settings.

SAVE ...

Save the current fractal and output settings to a file.

PRINT

Starts printing (If enough memory is available remains the calculated
image in the buffer).

PRINT BUFFER

Starts printing the buffer contents.

ABOUT

Shows some about information.

QUIT

Leaves PrintFractal.

@EndNode

@Node "MENU (BUFFER)"
@Next "MENU (SETTINGS)"
@Prev "MENU (PROJECT)"
@Toc  "Main"

BUFFER MENU

CLEAR BUFFER

Clears the buffer.

@EndNode

@Node "MENU (SETTINGS)"
@Next "PRINTING"
@Prev "MENU (BUFFER)"
@Toc  "Main"

SETTINGS MENU

SINGLE, DOUBLE OR EXTENDED PRECISION

Here you can choose with which precision PrintFractal is going to
calculate the picture. The fastest mode for computer without floating
point unit is 'single' with the fast floating point format (FFP) from
motorola. If you have a mathematical coprocessor you should always
select 'extended (FPU)'.

USE BUFFER ?

If this menu is selected PrintFractal will try to calculate the
complete image in memory. After printing you can start another print
using the menu PROJECT/PRINT BUFFER.
Disable this option if PrintFractal runs out of memory.

PREVIEW

In this submenu you're able to select if the preview image should be
small or big.

Additionally you can select if you want to see a statistic window after
calculating the preview.

OUTPUT

Select if you want to print the image in horizontal or vertical
orientation.

Additionally you can select if you want to see a statistic window after
printing the image.

LOAD SETTINGS

Loads the last saved settings.

SAVE SETTINGS

Saves the actual settings.

@EndNode

@Node "PRINTING"
@Next "REXX USAGE"
@Prev "MENU (SETTINGS)"
@Toc  "Main"

6. PRINTING

Before you start printing make sure that your printer is turned on
and has some paper inserted.

Before printing you could change the print density in the system prefs
editor 'PrinterGfx'.

After you've selected to print, the program tries to allocate memory for
the image (depending on the size and the print density). If sucessful,
it starts to calculate the image.
If you've selected the option 'Use buffer' PrintFractal tries to
calculate to full image in memory. For that it requires a large memory
block. But you are able to print some copies by using the menu
'Project/Print buffer'.

During the calculation a progess bar will be displayed.

@EndNode

@Node "REXX USAGE"
@Next "REXX (ABOUT)"
@Prev "PRINTING"
@Toc  "Main"

7. REXX

PrintFractal has an ARexx port which makes it possible to control
various functions of the program by using the script language ARexx.

PrintFractal supports the following commands:

     @{" ABOUT                 " Link "REXX (ABOUT)"}
     @{" LOAD                  " Link "REXX (LOAD)"}
     @{" PREVIEW               " Link "REXX (PREVIEW)"}
     @{" PRINT                 " Link "REXX (PRINT)"}
     @{" QUIT                  " Link "REXX (QUIT)"}
     @{" SAVE                  " Link "REXX (SAVE)"}
     @{" SETFRACTAL            " Link "REXX (SETFRACTAL)"}
     @{" TOBACK                " Link "REXX (TOBACK)"}
     @{" TOFRONT               " Link "REXX (TOFRONT)"}


Note:
The rexx port of PrintFractal is still under construction.

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (ABOUT)"
@Next "REXX (LOAD)"
@Prev "REXX"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

ABOUT

No parameter. Shows some about information.

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (LOAD)"
@Next "REXX (PREVIEW)"
@Prev "REXX (ABOUT)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

LOAD FILE

With this command a settings file can be loaded. Therefore a file
name must be given after the command. If no file name is given a file
requester will pop up.
The keyword FILE is optional.

Example:
LOAD Harddisk:Fractals/Dragon.pf

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (PREVIEW)"
@Next "REXX (PRINT)"
@Prev "REXX (LOAD)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

PREVIEW SIZE

Starts the calculation of the preview window. Optionally a size para-
meter ('SMALL' of 'LARGE') can be given.

Examples:
PREVIEW
PREVIEW SIZE=SMALL
PREVIEW LARGE

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (PRINT)"
@Next "REXX (QUIT)"
@Prev "REXX (PREVIEW)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

PRINT

Starts printing the current fractal using the actual settings.

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (QUIT)"
@Next "REXX (SAVE)"
@Prev "REXX (PRINT)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

QUIT

Leaves PrintFractal.

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (SAVE)"
@Next "REXX (SETFRACTAL)"
@Prev "REXX (QUIT)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

SAVE FILE, FORCE/S

With this command a parameter file containing the actual values can
be created. Therefore a file name must be given. If this file already
exists, the execution is cancelled. The existing file can be
overwritten by selecting the switch FORCE.
If no file name is given a file requester will pop up.

Examples:
SAVE WORK:Mandelbrot_8.pf
SAVE
SAVE FILE="New parameters.pf" FORCE

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (SETFRACTAL)"
@Next "REXX (TOBACK)"
@Prev "REXX (SAVE)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

SETFRACTAL TYPE/K,L=LEFT/K,R=RIGHT/K,T=TOP/K,B=BOTTOM/K,
           I=ITERATIONS/N/K,REAL/K,IMAG/K,LIMIT/N/K,
           MODE/N/K,BORDER/N/K,W=WIDTH/K,H=HEIGHT/K

This command is used to set the parameters of the fractal.

Option		Parameter

TYPE		Use 'MANDELBROT' or 'JULIA' to set the type of fractal.

LEFT,
RIGHT,
TOP,
BOTTOM,
REAL,
IMAG		The parameter must be a string representing a floating
			point number.

WIDTH,
HEIGHT		The parameter must be a string representing a positive
			floating point number.

ITERATIONS	Sets the maximum number of calculation steps (positive
			integer).

LIMIT		Sets the limit of the process (positive integer).

MODE		Use 0 for mono mode or 1 for alternate mode.

BORDER		Positive integer (0-7)


If possible, SETFRACTAL should be called once with all options instead
of calling it often with single options, because the main window will
be refreshed after each call.

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (TOBACK)"
@Next "REXX (TOFRONT)"
@Prev "REXX (SETFRACTAL)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

TOBACK

Moves the main window behind all other windows.

@EndNode

@Node "REXX (TOFRONT)"
@Next "AUTHOR"
@Prev "REXX (TOBACK)"
@Toc  "Main"

REXX

TOFRONT

Moves the window in front of all other windows.

@EndNode

